Kenji Tsuda.about: What strikes the listener is a succession of sounds that are abrupt and seemingly disconnected. Yet, this is not improvisational chaos. Rather, it inverts the very logic of sound, confronting us with the fundamental question: "What does it mean to listen?" Electronic noise, environmental sounds, and rhythms on the verge of collapse—these elements may appear random at first glance, yet they directly access the subconscious auditory sense, creating unpredictable psychological disturbances.

Kenji Tsuda.title: aegrotare simulare
Kenji Tsuda.about: This album is an electronic sound work themed around “May Blues,” a phenomenon unique to Japan. After the initial excitement of a new life fades, a creeping sense of fatigue, anxiety, and the struggle to adapt are expressed through intentionally jarring noise, dissonance, and fragmented melodies. The coldness of digital sounds and repetitive mechanical rhythms highlight the loneliness and sense of stagnation felt in modern society. Occasionally, faint melodies and environmental sounds are woven in, symbolizing the wavering hope and desire for healing. Through this world of discomforting sounds, listeners are invited to confront the May Blues that may lurk within themselves. When overwhelmed by the noise and pressures of daily life, we hope this album encourages you to reflect on the true nature of “May Blues” deep within your heart.

Kenji Tsuda.title: Corpus Sonorum Sine Finibus
Kenji Tsuda.about: This work, Corpus Sonorum Sine Finibus ("Sound Body Without Boundaries"), is an album that deliberately excludes deliberate reasoning and intentional construction, exploring a world of electronic sound rich in chance and improvisation. It deconstructs conventional musical order through the generation and disappearance of sounds, fragmentation and reconstruction, and the unpredictable insertion of noise and silence, blurring the very boundaries of auditory experience. Each track intertwines fluid and abstract sonic materials, where the very existence of sound sometimes wavers, expanding into amorphous spaces. Listeners are invited to surrender themselves to pure sonic phenomena beyond meaning or narrative, discovering new orders and beauty within accidental resonances. Corpus Sonorum Sine Finibus is a challenging and poetic collection that dismantles musical frameworks and presents an uncharted sonic horizon woven from chance and abstraction.

Kenji Tsuda.title: Interferentia Inopinata
Kenji Tsuda.about: "Interferentia Inopinata" (Unexpected Interference) is a collection of electronic sound works themed around chance and inevitable intersections. Rather than adhering to predetermined order or structure, this album pursues a unique sonic experience born from unexpected encounters and interactions between sounds. Each track intricately weaves together layers of subtle noise, sudden appearances of alien timbres, and irregularly intersecting rhythms and reverberations—phenomena that are truly "unexpected." These interferences often generate dissonance or chaos, yet at other times, they bring about accidental beauty and harmony. By surrendering themselves to the unpredictable flow of sound, listeners may gradually experience the boundaries of reality becoming blurred. "Interferentia Inopinata" is a challenging and poetic album that proposes a new sensory world beyond the conventional framework of music.

Kenji Tsuda.title: Motivatio Diminuta
Kenji Tsuda.about:
‘Motivatio Diminuta’ is an electronic work that allows listeners to re-experience the invisible transformation known as the decline of motivation through sound. It depicts intangible languor, diluted will, and particles of emotion drifting between silence and faint movement within multilayered soundscapes.
Fragments of sound sometimes diffuse like mist, at other times accumulate unseen weight, settling deep within the listener. The contours of melody and rhythm melt ambiguously, and the continuity of past and future remains indistinct. Various resonances seep into one another, losing their outlines as they continue to drift.
